# Testing Standards

## Structure
- Mirror src/ structure in tests/
- Prefix test files with test_
- Use descriptive test names: test_<function>_<scenario>_<expected>

## Fixtures
- Define shared fixtures in conftest.py
- Scope fixtures appropriately (function, module, session)
- Use factory fixtures for complex objects

## Coverage
- Target 80% line coverage minimum
- 100% coverage on config/ and contract tests
- Run with: pytest --cov=src/{{ project_slug }} --cov-report=term-missing

## Contract Tests
- tests/contract/ validates environment parity, env_spec drift, dev/prod guardrails
- These tests must pass in all modes (offline, local-live, prod)

## Assertions
- Use specific assertions (assert x == y, not assert x)
- Test both happy path and error cases
- Use pytest.raises for expected exceptions

## Scope & Hygiene
- When adding a new Python directory to the repo, immediately add it to the lint/typecheck targets in verify scripts and CI config.
- Test data must be complete across all stores the system uses. If the runtime reads from both a search index and a metadata database, test fixtures must populate both — indexing one store alone causes false failures.

## Mode Isolation
- Always use an explicit mode fixture (e.g., `_pin_offline_mode` from conftest.py) in any test that exercises mode-gated code. Never rely on APP_MODE defaulting to offline — the developer's shell may have it set to `local-live`.
- Tests in `local-live` mode must stub any validators or services that require real cloud credentials.
- Mode-gated singletons (e.g., RuntimeConfig cache, retriever cache) must expose a cache-clear function. Test fixtures must call it when changing APP_MODE to prevent stale state across tests.
